Wash and dry produce.

Dice @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces.

Place potatoes in a #medium pot{} with enough salted water to cover by 2 inches.
Bring to a boil and cook until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Reserve ½ cup potato
cooking liquid, then drain. Return potatoes to pot; cover to keep warm.

While potatoes cook, trim and thinly slice @button mushrooms{4%ounce}
(skip if your mushrooms are pre-sliced!). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2},
separating whites from greens.

Pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat. Add chicken and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per
side.

> Swap in pork or beef for chicken; for pork cook until browned and cooked
> through, 4-6 minutes per side, or cook beef to desired doneness, 4-7 minutes
> per side.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #cutting board{} and tent with #foil{} to keep
warm. Wipe out pan.

To pot with potatoes, add @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon} and ½ TBSP
@butter{1.5%tablespoon}; mash until smooth with a #potato masher{}, adding splashes
of reserved potato cooking liquid as needed.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for chicken over medium heat. Add mushrooms
and scallion whites; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and slightly
crispy, ~{5-7%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Add @balsamic vinegar{5%teaspoon}, @mushroom stock concentrate{1%unit},
¼ cup water, 1 TBSP butter, and @sugar{½%teaspoon}; cook, stirring, until
mushrooms are coated and sauce has thickened slightly, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> If sauce seems too thick, stir in more water 1 TBSP at a time.

> Use pan used for chicken or beef here.

Slice chicken crosswise.

Divide chicken and mashed potatoes between plates. Spoon mushroom sauce over
chicken and garnish with scallion greens. Serve.

> Slice chicken or beef against the grain.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.